\i0 \cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb5 Hi Kumar,\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb5 Great question. The term \'93linear function\'94 actually refers to two separate (but related) concepts (see\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_function"}}{\fldrslt \cf2 \strokec2 http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_function}}\'a0for more detail).\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb5 1) A polynomial of degree 0 or 1, i.e. f(x) = ax + b\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb5 2) a \'93linear map\'94, meaning a function that has the properties that scaling the inputs scales the outputs, f(c*a) = c*f(a), and adding the inputs adds the outputs, f(a + b) = f(a) + f(b).\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb5 The function f(x) = x + 3 meets the first definition (polynomial of degree 1), and it is a straight line when drawn. But it doesn\'92t have the linear input/output relationship. For example, f(1) = 4, but f(2) = 5. We doubled the input, but did not double the input.\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb5 The main reason a line is not \'93linear\'94 (in the linear map sense) is because of that + b term, which is +3 in our case. That +3 is the same amount, no matter how the input changes.\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb5 The two meanings are easily-confused, and did confuse me for a long time! Linear algebra refers to deal with behavior of functions that are linear maps.\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \u8232 \u8232 \
